<h3 id="metrics-for-assessing-fund-performance">Metrics for Assessing Fund Performance</h3>

<ul>
  <li>Common Metrics
    <ul>
      <li>Annual Return
        <ul>
          <li>metric:
            <ul>
              <li><code class="highlighter-rouge">(value[end] / value[star])) -1</code></li>
              <li><code class="highlighter-rouge">(value[end] - value[start])/value[start]</code></li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>Example: $100 to $110
            <ul>
              <li><code class="highlighter-rouge">(110/100) -1 = 0.1 = 10%</code></li>
              <li><code class="highlighter-rouge">(110-100)/100 = 0.1 = 10%</code></li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Risk
        <ul>
          <li>å®šä¹‰é£é™©ï¼š<mark>Standard deviation of return</mark>
            <ul>
              <li>daily return</li>
            </ul>

            <div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>  //æ—¥å›æŠ¥ä¿å‡†å·®
  daily_rets[i] = (value[i]/value[i-1]) -1
  std_metrics = stdev(daily_rets)
</code></pre></div>            </div>
          </li>
          <li>Draw down
            <ul>
              <li>æœ€å¤§è·Œå¹…</li>
              <li>å¹³å‡è·Œå¹…</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><mark>Reward/Risk</mark>
    <ul>
      <li>æ”¶ç›Šé£é™©æ¯”ï¼ŒHow much reward you are getting for your risk?</li>
      <li><strong>Sharpe Ratio</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Most â€œimportantâ€ measure of asset performance.</li>
          <li>How well does the return of an asset compensate the investor for the risk taken</li>
          <li><mark>The higher the Sharpe ratio the better.</mark></li>
          <li>When comparing two assets each with the same return, higher ratio gives more return for the same risk.</li>
        </ul>

        <math display="block">
      <mi>S</mi>
      <mo>=</mo>
      <mfrac>
          <mrow>
              <mi>E</mi>
              <mo stretchy="false">[</mo>
              <mi>R</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>R</mi><mi>f</mi></msub>
              <mo stretchy="false">]</mo>
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
              <mi>Ïƒ</mi>
          </mrow>
      </mfrac>
      <mo>=</mo>
      <mfrac>
          <mrow>
              <mi>E</mi>
              <mo stretchy="false">[</mo>
              <mi>R</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>R</mi><mi>f</mi></msub>
              <mo stretchy="false">]</mo>
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
              <msqrt>
                  <mi>var</mi>
                  <mi>E</mi>
                  <mo stretchy="false">[</mo>
                  <mi>R</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>R</mi><mi>f</mi></msub>
                  <mo stretchy="false">]</mo>
              </msqrt>
          </mrow>
     	</mfrac>
     	<mo>=</mo>
     	<mi>K</mi><mo>*</mo>
     	<mfrac>
     		<mtext>dailyRet</mtext>
     		<mtext>std(dailyret)</mtext>
     	</mfrac>
  	</math>

        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>seudo code</p>

            <div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>  metric = k * mean(daily_rets)/stdev(daily_rets)
  # k = sqrt(250) for daily returns
  # 250: days in a trading year
</code></pre></div>            </div>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Sortino Ratio
        <ul>
          <li>Sortino ratio only penalizes for negative volatility in the calculation of risk.</li>
          <li>Sharpe ratio penalizes for both positive and negative volatility.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Jensenâ€™s Alpha</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Example</li>
</ul>

